{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_1e96bbea96254c4598008f32","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t<!-- pyml disable-next-line first-line-heading -->\n2\t[![jazzband-image]][jazzband]\n3\t[![pypi][pypi-image]][pypi]\n4\t[![pyversions][pyversions-image]][pyversions]\n5\t[![pre-commit][pre-commit-image]][pre-commit]\n6\t[![buildstatus-gha][buildstatus-gha-image]][buildstatus-gha]\n7\t[![codecov][codecov-image]][codecov]\n8\t[![Matrix Room Badge]][Matrix Room]\n9\t[![Matrix Space Badge]][Matrix Space]\n10\t[![discord-chat-image]][discord-chat]\n11\t\n12\t# pip-tools = pip-compile + pip-sync\n13\t\n14\tA set of command line tools to help you keep your `pip`-based packages fresh,\n15\teven when you've pinned them. You do pin them, right? (In building your Python\n16\tapplication and its dependencies for production, you want to make sure that\n17\tyour builds are predictable and deterministic.)\n18\t\n19\t[![pip-tools overview for phase II][pip-tools-overview]][pip-tools-overview]\n20\t\n21\t## Installation\n22\t\n23\tSimilar to `pip`, `pip-tools` must be installed in each of your project's\n24\t[virtual environments](https://packaging.python.org/tutorials/installing-packages/#creating-virtual-environments):\n25\t\n26\t```console\n27\t$ source /path/to/venv/bin/activate\n28\t(venv) $ python -m pip install pip-tools\n29\t```\n30\t\n31\t**Note**: all of the remaining example commands assume you've activated your\n32\tproject's virtual environment.\n33\t\n34\t## Example usage for `pip-compile`\n35\t\n36\tThe `pip-compile` command lets you compile a `requirements.txt` file from\n37\tyour dependencies, specified in either `pyproject.toml`, `setup.cfg`,\n38\t`setup.py`, or `requirements.in`.\n39\t\n40\tRun it with `pip-compile` or `python -m piptools compile` (or\n41\t`pipx run --spec pip-tools pip-compile` if `pipx` was installed with the\n42\tappropriate Python version). If you use multiple Python versions, you can also\n43\trun `py -X.Y -m piptools compile` on Windows and\n44\t`pythonX.Y -m piptools compile` on other systems.\n45\t\n46\t`pip-compile` should be run from the same virtual environment as your\n47\tproject so conditional dependencies that require a specific Python version,\n48\tor other environment markers, resolve relative to your project's\n49\tenvironment.\n50\t\n51\t**Note**: If `pip-compile` finds an existing `requirements.txt` file that\n52\tfulfils the dependencies then no changes will be made, even if updates are\n53\tavailable. To compile from scratch, first delete the existing\n54\t`requirements.txt` file, or see\n55\t[Updating requirements](#updating-requirements)\n56\tfor alternative approaches.\n57\t\n58\t### Requirements from `pyproject.toml`\n59\t\n60\tThe `pyproject.toml` file is the\n61\t[latest standard](https://peps.python.org/pep-0621/) for configuring\n62\tpackages and applications, and is recommended for new projects. `pip-compile`\n63\tsupports both installing your `project.dependencies` as well as your\n64\t`project.optional-dependencies`. Thanks to the fact that this is an\n65\tofficial standard, you can use `pip-compile` to pin the dependencies\n66\tin projects that use modern standards-adhering packaging tools like\n67\t[Setuptools](https://setuptools.pypa.io), [Hatch](https://hatch.pypa.io/)\n68\tor [flit](https://flit.pypa.io/).\n69\t\n70\tSuppose you have a 'foobar' Python application that is packaged using\n71\t`Setuptools`, and you want to pin it for production. You can declare the\n72\tproject metadata as:\n73\t\n74\t```toml\n75\t[build-system]\n76\trequires = [\"setuptools\", \"setuptools-scm\"]\n77\tbuild-backend = \"setuptools.build_meta\"\n78\t\n79\t[project]\n80\trequires-python = \">=3.9\"\n81\tname = \"foobar\"\n82\tdynamic = [\"dependencies\", \"optional-dependencies\"]\n83\t\n84\t[tool.setuptools.dynamic]\n85\tdependencies = { file = [\"requirements.in\"] }\n86\toptional-dependencies.test = { file = [\"requirements-test.txt\"] }\n87\t\n88\t```\n89\t\n90\tIf you have a Django application that is packaged using `Hatch`, and you\n91\twant to pin it for production. You also want to pin your development tools\n92\tin a separate pin file. You declare `django` as a dependency and create an\n93\toptional dependency `dev` that includes `pytest`:\n94\t\n95\t```toml\n96\t[build-system]\n97\trequires = [\"hatchling\"]\n98\tbuild-backend = \"hatchling.build\"\n99\t\n100\t[project]\n101\tname = \"my-cool-django-app\"\n102\tversion = \"42\"\n103\tdependencies = [\"django\"]\n104\t\n105\t[project.optional-dependencies]\n106\tdev = [\"pytest\"]\n107\t```\n108\t\n109\tYou can produce your pin files as easily as:\n110\t\n111\t```console\n112\t$ pip-compile -o requirements.txt pyproject.toml\n113\t#\n114\t# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n115\t# by the following command:\n116\t#\n117\t#    pip-compile --output-file=requirements.txt pyproject.toml\n118\t#\n119\tasgiref==3.6.0\n120\t    # via django\n121\tdjango==4.1.7\n122\t    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\n123\tsqlparse==0.4.3\n124\t    # via django\n125\t\n126\t$ pip-compile --extra dev -o dev-requirements.txt pyproject.toml\n127\t#\n128\t# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n129\t# by the following command:\n130\t#\n131\t#    pip-compile --extra=dev --output-file=dev-requirements.txt pyproject.toml\n132\t#\n133\tasgiref==3.6.0\n134\t    # via django\n135\tattrs==22.2.0\n136\t    # via pytest\n137\tdjango==4.1.7\n138\t    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\n139\texceptiongroup==1.1.1\n140\t    # via pytest\n141\tiniconfig==2.0.0\n142\t    # via pytest\n143\tpackaging==23.0\n144\t    # via pytest\n145\tpluggy==1.0.0\n146\t    # via pytest\n147\tpytest==7.2.2\n148\t    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\n149\tsqlparse==0.4.3\n150\t    # via django\n151\ttomli==2.0.1\n152\t    # via pytest\n153\t```\n154\t\n155\tThis is great for both pinning your applications, but also to keep the CI\n156\tof your open-source Python package stable.\n157\t\n158\t### Requirements from `setup.py` and `setup.cfg`\n159\t\n160\t`pip-compile` has also full support for `setup.py`- and\n161\t`setup.cfg`-based projects that use `setuptools`.\n162\t\n163\tJust define your dependencies and extras as usual and run\n164\t`pip-compile` as above.\n165\t\n166\t### Requirements from `requirements.in`\n167\t\n168\tYou can also use plain text files for your requirements (e.g. if you don't\n169\twant your application to be a package). To use a `requirements.in` file to\n170\tdeclare the Django dependency:\n171\t\n172\t```text\n173\t# requirements.in\n174\tdjango\n175\t```\n176\t\n177\tNow, run `pip-compile requirements.in`:\n178\t\n179\t```console\n180\t$ pip-compile requirements.in\n181\t#\n182\t# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n183\t# by the following command:\n184\t#\n185\t#    pip-compile requirements.in\n186\t#\n187\tasgiref==3.6.0\n188\t    # via django\n189\tdjango==4.1.7\n190\t    # via -r requirements.in\n191\tsqlparse==0.4.3\n192\t    # via django\n193\t```\n194\t\n195\tAnd it will produce your `requirements.txt`, with all the Django dependencies\n196\t(and all underlying dependencies) pinned.\n197\t\n198\t(updating-requirements)=\n199\t\n200\t### Updating requirements\n201\t\n202\t`pip-compile` generates a `requirements.txt` file using the latest versions\n203\tthat fulfil the dependencies you specify in the supported files.\n204\t\n205\tIf `pip-compile` finds an existing `requirements.txt` file that fulfils the\n206\tdependencies then no changes will be made, even if updates are available.\n207\t\n208\tTo force `pip-compile` to update all packages in an existing\n209\t`requirements.txt`, run `pip-compile --upgrade`.\n210\t\n211\tTo update a specific package to the latest or a specific version use the\n212\t`--upgrade-package` or `-P` flag:\n213\t\n214\t```console\n215\t# only update the django package\n216\t$ pip-compile --upgrade-package django\n217\t\n218\t# update both the django and requests packages\n219\t$ pip-compile --upgrade-package django --upgrade-package requests\n220\t\n221\t# update the django package to the latest, and requests to v2.0.0\n222\t$ pip-compile --upgrade-package django --upgrade-package requests==2.0.0\n223\t```\n224\t\n225\tYou can combine `--upgrade` and `--upgrade-package` in one command, to\n226\tprovide constraints on the allowed upgrades. For example to upgrade all\n227\tpackages whilst constraining requests to the latest version less than 3.0:\n228\t\n229\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n230\t```console\n231\t$ pip-compile --upgrade --upgrade-package 'requests<3.0'\n232\t```\n233\t\n234\t### Understanding output file behavior\n235\t\n236\tWhen you run `pip-compile`, it reads any existing output file (e.g.,\n237\t`requirements.txt`) and uses the versions specified there as constraints.\n238\tThis ensures that the output is stable -- `pip-compile` will prefer to\n239\tuse existing pinned versions.\n240\t\n241\tWhen upgrading packages or adding new packages to the input,\n242\tit is possible for the existing pins to conflict with new packages. In such cases,\n243\t`pip-compile` will update the pins and emit a warning\n244\t(e.g., `Discarding foo=1.2.3 to proceed`).\n245\t\n246\tIn order to resolve dependencies afresh, `pip-compile` provides the following options:\n247\t\n248\t- `--upgrade` / `-U` flag to upgrade all packages\n249\t- `--upgrade-package <package>`/`-P <package>` to upgrade specific packages\n250\t\n251\t### Using hashes\n252\t\n253\tIf you would like to use _Hash-Checking Mode_ available in `pip` since\n254\tversion 8.0, `pip-compile` offers `--generate-hashes` flag:\n255\t\n256\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 18 line-length -->\n257\t```console\n258\t$ pip-compile --generate-hashes requirements.in\n259\t#\n260\t# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n261\t# by the following command:\n262\t#\n263\t#    pip-compile --generate-hashes requirements.in\n264\t#\n265\tasgiref==3.6.0 \\\n266\t    --hash=sha256:71e68008da809b957b7ee4b43dbccff33d1b23519fb8344e33f049897077afac \\\n267\t    --hash=sha256:9567dfe7bd8d3c8c892227827c41cce860b368104c3431da67a0c5a65a949506\n268\t    # via django\n269\tdjango==4.1.7 \\\n270\t    --hash=sha256:44f714b81c5f190d9d2ddad01a532fe502fa01c4cb8faf1d081f4264ed15dcd8 \\\n271\t    --hash=sha256:f2f431e75adc40039ace496ad3b9f17227022e8b11566f4b363da44c7e44761e\n272\t    # via -r requirements.in\n273\tsqlparse==0.4.3 \\\n274\t    --hash=sha256:0323c0ec29cd52bceabc1b4d9d579e311f3e4961b98d174201d5622a23b85e34 \\\n275\t    --hash=sha256:69ca804846bb114d2ec380e4360a8a340db83f0ccf3afceeb1404df028f57268\n276\t    # via django\n277\t```\n278\t\n279\t### Output File\n280\t\n281\tTo output the pinned requirements in a filename other than\n282\t`requirements.txt`, use `--output-file`. This might be useful for compiling\n283\tmultiple files, for example with different constraints on django to test a\n284\tlibrary with both versions using [tox](https://tox.readthedocs.io/en/latest/):\n285\t\n286\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n287\t```console\n288\t$ pip-compile --upgrade-package 'django<1.0' --output-file requirements-django0x.txt\n289\t$ pip-compile --upgrade-package 'django<2.0' --output-file requirements-django1x.txt\n290\t```\n291\t\n292\tOr to output to standard output, use `--output-file=-`:\n293\t\n294\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n295\t```console\n296\t$ pip-compile --output-file=- > requirements.txt\n297\t$ pip-compile - --output-file=- < requirements.in > requirements.txt\n298\t```\n299\t\n300\t### Forwarding options to `pip`\n301\t\n302\tAny valid `pip` flags or arguments may be passed on with `pip-compile`'s\n303\t`--pip-args` option, e.g.\n304\t\n305\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n306\t```console\n307\t$ pip-compile requirements.in --pip-args \"--retries 10 --timeout 30\"\n308\t```\n309\t\n310\t### Configuration\n311\t\n312\tYou can define project-level defaults for `pip-compile` and `pip-sync` by\n313\twriting them to a configuration file in the same directory as your requirements\n314\tinput files (or the current working directory if piping input from stdin).\n315\tBy default, both `pip-compile` and `pip-sync` will look first\n316\tfor a `.pip-tools.toml` file and then in your `pyproject.toml`. You can\n317\talso specify an alternate TOML configuration file with the `--config` option.\n318\t\n319\tIt is possible to specify configuration values both globally and command-\n320\tspecific.\n321\tFor example, to by default generate `pip` hashes in the resulting\n322\trequirements file output, you can specify in a configuration file:\n323\t\n324\t```toml\n325\t[tool.pip-tools]\n326\tgenerate-hashes = true\n327\t```\n328\t\n329\tOptions to `pip-compile` and `pip-sync` that may be used more than once\n330\tmust be defined as lists in a configuration file, even if they only have one\n331\tvalue.\n332\t\n333\t`pip-tools` supports default values for [all valid command-line\n334\tflags](/cli/index.md) of its subcommands. Configuration keys may contain\n335\tunderscores instead of dashes, so the above could also be specified in this\n336\tformat:\n337\t\n338\t```toml\n339\t[tool.pip-tools]\n340\tgenerate_hashes = true\n341\t```\n342\t\n343\tConfiguration defaults specific to `pip-compile` and `pip-sync` can be put\n344\tbeneath separate sections. For example, to by default perform a dry-run with\n345\t`pip-compile`:\n346\t\n347\t```toml\n348\t[tool.pip-tools.compile] # \"sync\" for pip-sync\n349\tdry-run = true\n350\t```\n351\t\n352\tThis does not affect the `pip-sync` command, which also has a `--dry-run`\n353\toption.\n354\tNote that local settings take preference over the global ones of the same name,\n355\twhenever both are declared, thus this would also make `pip-compile` generate\n356\thashes, but discard the global dry-run setting:\n357\t\n358\t```toml\n359\t[tool.pip-tools]\n360\tgenerate-hashes = true\n361\tdry-run = true\n362\t\n363\t[tool.pip-tools.compile]\n364\tdry-run = false\n365\t```\n366\t\n367\tYou might be wrapping the `pip-compile` command in another script. To avoid\n368\tconfusing consumers of your custom script you can override the update command\n369\tgenerated at the top of requirements files by setting the\n370\t`CUSTOM_COMPILE_COMMAND` environment variable.\n371\t\n372\t```console\n373\t$ CUSTOM_COMPILE_COMMAND=\"./pipcompilewrapper\" pip-compile requirements.in\n374\t#\n375\t# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n376\t# by the following command:\n377\t#\n378\t#    ./pipcompilewrapper\n379\t#\n380\tasgiref==3.6.0\n381\t    # via django\n382\tdjango==4.1.7\n383\t    # via -r requirements.in\n384\tsqlparse==0.4.3\n385\t    # via django\n386\t```\n387\t\n388\t### Workflow for layered requirements\n389\t\n390\tIf you have different environments that you need to install different but\n391\tcompatible packages for, then you can create layered requirements files and use\n392\tone layer to constrain the other.\n393\t\n394\tFor example, if you have a Django project where you want the newest `2.1`\n395\trelease in production and when developing you want to use the Django debug\n396\ttoolbar, then you can create two `*.in` files, one for each layer:\n397\t\n398\t```text\n399\t# requirements.in\n400\tdjango<2.2\n401\t```\n402\t\n403\tAt the top of the development requirements `dev-requirements.in` you use `-c\n404\trequirements.txt` to constrain the dev requirements to packages already\n405\tselected for production in `requirements.txt`.\n406\t\n407\t```text\n408\t# dev-requirements.in\n409\t-c requirements.txt\n410\tdjango-debug-toolbar<2.2\n411\t```\n412\t\n413\tFirst, compile `requirements.txt` as usual:\n414\t\n415\t```text\n416\t$ pip-compile\n417\t#\n418\t# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n419\t# by the following command:\n420\t#\n421\t#    pip-compile\n422\t#\n423\tdjango==2.1.15\n424\t    # via -r requirements.in\n425\tpytz==2023.3\n426\t    # via django\n427\t```\n428\t\n429\tNow compile the dev requirements and the `requirements.txt` file is used as\n430\ta constraint:\n431\t\n432\t```console\n433\t$ pip-compile dev-requirements.in\n434\t#\n435\t# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n436\t# by the following command:\n437\t#\n438\t#    pip-compile dev-requirements.in\n439\t#\n440\tdjango==2.1.15\n441\t    # via\n442\t    #   -c requirements.txt\n443\t    #   django-debug-toolbar\n444\tdjango-debug-toolbar==2.1\n445\t    # via -r dev-requirements.in\n446\tpytz==2023.3\n447\t    # via\n448\t    #   -c requirements.txt\n449\t    #   django\n450\tsqlparse==0.4.3\n451\t    # via django-debug-toolbar\n452\t```\n453\t\n454\tAs you can see above, even though a `2.2` release of Django is available, the\n455\tdev requirements only include a `2.1` version of Django because they were\n456\tconstrained. Now both compiled requirements files can be installed safely in\n457\tthe dev environment.\n458\t\n459\tTo install requirements in production stage use:\n460\t\n461\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n462\t```console\n463\t$ pip-sync\n464\t```\n465\t\n466\tYou can install requirements in development stage by:\n467\t\n468\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n469\t```console\n470\t$ pip-sync requirements.txt dev-requirements.txt\n471\t```\n472\t\n473\t### Version control integration\n474\t\n475\tYou might use `pip-compile` as a hook for the\n476\t[pre-commit](https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit).\n477\tSee [pre-commit docs](https://pre-commit.com/) for instructions.\n478\tSample `.pre-commit-config.yaml`:\n479\t\n480\t```yaml\n481\trepos:\n482\t  - repo: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools\n483\t    rev: 7.4.1\n484\t    hooks:\n485\t      - id: pip-compile\n486\t```\n487\t\n488\tYou might want to customize `pip-compile` args by configuring `args` and/or\n489\t`files`, for example:\n490\t\n491\t```yaml\n492\trepos:\n493\t  - repo: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools\n494\t    rev: 7.4.1\n495\t    hooks:\n496\t      - id: pip-compile\n497\t        files: ^requirements/production\\.(in|txt)$\n498\t        args: [--index-url=https://example.com, requirements/production.in]\n499\t```\n500\t\n501\tIf you have multiple requirement files make sure you create a hook for each\n502\tfile.\n503\t\n504\t```yaml\n505\trepos:\n506\t  - repo: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools\n507\t    rev: 7.4.1\n508\t    hooks:\n509\t      - id: pip-compile\n510\t        name: pip-compile setup.py\n511\t        files: ^(setup\\.py|requirements\\.txt)$\n512\t      - id: pip-compile\n513\t        name: pip-compile requirements-dev.in\n514\t        args: [requirements-dev.in]\n515\t        files: ^requirements-dev\\.(in|txt)$\n516\t      - id: pip-compile\n517\t        name: pip-compile requirements-lint.in\n518\t        args: [requirements-lint.in]\n519\t        files: ^requirements-lint\\.(in|txt)$\n520\t      - id: pip-compile\n521\t        name: pip-compile requirements.in\n522\t        args: [requirements.in]\n523\t        files: ^requirements\\.(in|txt)$\n524\t```\n525\t\n526\t### Example usage for `pip-sync`\n527\t\n528\tNow that you have a `requirements.txt`, you can use `pip-sync` to update\n529\tyour virtual environment to reflect exactly what's in there. This will\n530\tinstall/upgrade/uninstall everything necessary to match the\n531\t`requirements.txt` contents.\n532\t\n533\tRun it with `pip-sync` or `python -m piptools sync`. If you use multiple\n534\tPython versions, you can also run `py -X.Y -m piptools sync` on Windows and\n535\t`pythonX.Y -m piptools sync` on other systems.\n536\t\n537\t`pip-sync` must be installed into and run from the same virtual\n538\tenvironment as your project to identify which packages to install\n539\tor upgrade.\n540\t\n541\t**Be careful**: `pip-sync` is meant to be used only with a\n542\t`requirements.txt` generated by `pip-compile`.\n543\t\n544\t```console\n545\t$ pip-sync\n546\tUninstalling flake8-2.4.1:\n547\t    Successfully uninstalled flake8-2.4.1\n548\tCollecting click==4.1\n549\t    Downloading click-4.1-py2.py3-none-any.whl (62kB)\n550\t    100% |................................| 65kB 1.8MB/s\n551\t    Found existing installation: click 4.0\n552\t    Uninstalling click-4.0:\n553\t        Successfully uninstalled click-4.0\n554\tSuccessfully installed click-4.1\n555\t```\n556\t\n557\tTo sync multiple `*.txt` dependency lists, just pass them in via command\n558\tline arguments, e.g.\n559\t\n560\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n561\t```console\n562\t$ pip-sync dev-requirements.txt requirements.txt\n563\t```\n564\t\n565\tPassing in empty arguments would cause it to default to `requirements.txt`.\n566\t\n567\tAny valid `pip install` flags or arguments may be passed with `pip-sync`'s\n568\t`--pip-args` option, e.g.\n569\t\n570\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n571\t```console\n572\t$ pip-sync requirements.txt --pip-args \"--no-cache-dir --no-deps\"\n573\t```\n574\t\n575\t**Note**: `pip-sync` will not upgrade or uninstall packaging tools like\n576\t`setuptools`, `pip`, or `pip-tools` itself.\n577\tUse `python -m pip install --upgrade` to upgrade those packages.\n578\t\n579\t### Should I commit `requirements.in` and `requirements.txt` to source control?\n580\t\n581\tGenerally, yes. If you want a reproducible environment installation available\n582\tfrom your source control, then yes, you should commit both `requirements.in`\n583\tand `requirements.txt` to source control.\n584\t\n585\tNote that if you are deploying on multiple Python environments (read the\n586\tsection below), then you must commit a separate output file for each Python\n587\tenvironment.\n588\tWe suggest to use the `{env}-requirements.txt` format\n589\t(ex: `win32-py3.7-requirements.txt`, `macos-py3.10-requirements.txt`,\n590\tetc.).\n591\t\n592\t### Cross-environment usage of `requirements.in`/`requirements.txt` and `pip-compile`\n593\t\n594\tThe dependencies of a package can change depending on the Python environment in\n595\twhich it is installed. Here, we define a Python environment as the combination\n596\tof Operating System, Python version (3.7, 3.8, etc.), and Python implementation\n597\t(CPython, PyPy, etc.). For an exact definition, refer to the possible\n598\tcombinations of [PEP 508 environment markers][environment-markers].\n599\t\n600\tAs the resulting `requirements.txt` can differ for each environment, users must\n601\texecute `pip-compile` **on each Python environment separately** to generate a\n602\t`requirements.txt` valid for each said environment. The same `requirements.in`\n603\tcan be used as the source file for all environments, using\n604\t[PEP 508 environment markers][environment-markers] as needed, the same way it\n605\twould be done for regular `pip` cross-environment usage.\n606\t\n607\tIf the generated `requirements.txt` remains exactly the same for all Python\n608\tenvironments, then it can be used across Python environments safely. **But**\n609\tusers should be careful as any package update can introduce\n610\tenvironment-dependent dependencies, making any newly generated\n611\t`requirements.txt` environment-dependent too.\n612\tAs a general rule, it's advised that users should still always execute\n613\t`pip-compile` on each targeted Python environment to avoid issues.\n614\t\n615\t### Maximizing reproducibility\n616\t\n617\t`pip-tools` is a great tool to improve the reproducibility of builds.\n618\tBut there are a few things to keep in mind.\n619\t\n620\t- `pip-compile` will produce different results in different environments as\n621\t  described in the previous section.\n622\t- `pip` must be used with the `PIP_CONSTRAINT` environment variable to lock\n623\t  dependencies in build environments as documented in\n624\t  [#8439](https://github.com/pypa/pip/issues/8439).\n625\t- Dependencies come from many sources.\n626\t\n627\tContinuing the `pyproject.toml` example from earlier, creating a single lock\n628\tfile could be done like:\n629\t\n630\t<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 7 line-length -->\n631\t```console\n632\t$ pip-compile --all-build-deps --all-extras --output-file=constraints.txt --strip-extras pyproject.toml\n633\t#\n634\t# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.9\n635\t# by the following command:\n636\t#\n637\t#    pip-compile --all-build-deps --all-extras --output-file=constraints.txt --strip-extras pyproject.toml\n638\t#\n639\tasgiref==3.5.2\n640\t    # via django\n641\tattrs==22.1.0\n642\t    # via pytest\n643\tbackports-zoneinfo==0.2.1\n644\t    # via django\n645\tdjango==4.1\n646\t    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\n647\teditables==0.3\n648\t    # via hatchling\n649\thatchling==1.11.1\n650\t    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml::build-system.requires)\n651\tiniconfig==1.1.1\n652\t    # via pytest\n653\tpackaging==21.3\n654\t    # via\n655\t    #   hatchling\n656\t    #   pytest\n657\tpathspec==0.10.2\n658\t    # via hatchling\n659\tpluggy==1.0.0\n660\t    # via\n661\t    #   hatchling\n662\t    #   pytest\n663\tpy==1.11.0\n664\t    # via pytest\n665\tpyparsing==3.0.9\n666\t    # via packaging\n667\tpytest==7.1.2\n668\t    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\n669\tsqlparse==0.4.2\n670\t    # via django\n671\ttomli==2.0.1\n672\t    # via\n673\t    #   hatchling\n674\t    #   pytest\n675\t```\n676\t\n677\tSome build backends may also request build dependencies dynamically using the\n678\t`get_requires_for_build_` hooks described in [PEP 517] and [PEP 660].\n679\tThis will be indicated in the output with one of the following suffixes:\n680\t\n681\t- `(pyproject.toml::build-system.backend::editable)`\n682\t- `(pyproject.toml::build-system.backend::sdist)`\n683\t- `(pyproject.toml::build-system.backend::wheel)`\n684\t\n685\t### Other useful tools\n686\t\n687\t- [pip-compile-multi](https://pip-compile-multi.rtfd.io) - pip-compile command\n688\t  wrapper for multiple cross-referencing requirements files.\n689\t- [pipdeptree](https://github.com/tox-dev/pipdeptree) to print the dependency\n690\t  tree of the installed packages.\n691\t- `requirements.in`/`requirements.txt` syntax highlighting:\n692\t  - [requirements.txt.vim](https://github.com/raimon49/requirements.txt.vim)\n693\t    for Vim.\n694\t  - [Python extension for VS Code].\n695\t  - [pip-requirements.el](https://github.com/Wilfred/pip-requirements.el) for\n696\t    Emacs.\n697\t\n698\t[Python extension for VS Code]:\n699\thttps://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=ms-python.python\n700\t\n701\t### Deprecations\n702\t\n703\tThis section lists `pip-tools` features that are currently deprecated.\n704\t\n705\t- In the next major release, the `--allow-unsafe` behavior will be enabled by\n706\t  default (https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/issues/989).\n707\t  Use `--no-allow-unsafe` to keep the old behavior. It is recommended\n708\t  to pass `--allow-unsafe` now to adapt to the upcoming change.\n709\t- The legacy resolver is deprecated and will be removed in future versions.\n710\t  The new default is `--resolver=backtracking`.\n711\t- In the next major release, the `--strip-extras` behavior will be enabled by\n712\t  default (https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/issues/1613).\n713\t  Use `--no-strip-extras` to keep the old behavior.\n714\t\n715\t### A Note on Resolvers\n716\t\n717\tYou can choose from either default backtracking resolver or the deprecated\n718\tlegacy resolver.\n719\t\n720\tThe legacy resolver will occasionally fail to resolve dependencies. The\n721\tbacktracking resolver is more robust, but can take longer to run in general.\n722\t\n723\tYou can continue using the legacy resolver with `--resolver=legacy` although\n724\tnote that it is deprecated and will be removed in a future release.\n725\t\n726\t[jazzband]: https://jazzband.co/\n727\t[jazzband-image]: https://jazzband.co/static/img/badge.svg\n728\t[pypi]: https://pypi.org/project/pip-tools/\n729\t[pypi-image]: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/pip-tools.svg\n730\t[pyversions]: https://pypi.org/project/pip-tools/\n731\t[pyversions-image]: https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/pip-tools.svg\n732\t[pre-commit]: https://results.pre-commit.ci/latest/github/jazzband/pip-tools/main\n733\t[pre-commit-image]: https://results.pre-commit.ci/badge/github/jazzband/pip-tools/main.svg\n734\t[buildstatus-gha]: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/actions?query=workflow%3ACI\n735\t[buildstatus-gha-image]: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/workflows/CI/badge.svg\n736\t[codecov]: https://codecov.io/gh/jazzband/pip-tools\n737\t[codecov-image]: https://codecov.io/gh/jazzband/pip-tools/branch/main/graph/badge.svg\n738\t[Matrix Room Badge]: https://img.shields.io/matrix/pip-tools:matrix.org?label=Discuss%20on%20Matrix%20at%20%23pip-tools%3Amatrix.org&logo=matrix&server_fqdn=matrix.org&style=flat\n739\t[Matrix Room]: https://matrix.to/#/%23pip-tools:matrix.org\n740\t[Matrix Space Badge]: https://img.shields.io/matrix/jazzband:matrix.org?label=Discuss%20on%20Matrix%20at%20%23jazzband%3Amatrix.org&logo=matrix&server_fqdn=matrix.org&style=flat\n741\t[Matrix Space]: https://matrix.to/#/%23jazzband:matrix.org\n742\t[pip-tools-overview]: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/raw/main/img/pip-tools-overview.svg\n743\t[environment-markers]: https://peps.python.org/pep-0508/#environment-markers\n744\t[PEP 517]: https://peps.python.org/pep-0517/\n745\t[PEP 660]: https://peps.python.org/pep-0660/\n746\t[discord-chat]: https://discord.gg/pypa\n747\t[discord-chat-image]: https://img.shields.io/discord/803025117553754132?label=Discord%20chat%20%23pip-tools&style=flat-square\n748\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b5305180-7b10-4a0d-8f6c-85a547bffd74","uuid":"0f78d0e5-8758-4566-9281-807329514e67","timestamp":"2026-04-06T14:12:07.712Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md","content":"<!-- pyml disable-next-line first-line-heading -->\n[![jazzband-image]][jazzband]\n[![pypi][pypi-image]][pypi]\n[![pyversions][pyversions-image]][pyversions]\n[![pre-commit][pre-commit-image]][pre-commit]\n[![buildstatus-gha][buildstatus-gha-image]][buildstatus-gha]\n[![codecov][codecov-image]][codecov]\n[![Matrix Room Badge]][Matrix Room]\n[![Matrix Space Badge]][Matrix Space]\n[![discord-chat-image]][discord-chat]\n\n# pip-tools = pip-compile + pip-sync\n\nA set of command line tools to help you keep your `pip`-based packages fresh,\neven when you've pinned them. You do pin them, right? (In building your Python\napplication and its dependencies for production, you want to make sure that\nyour builds are predictable and deterministic.)\n\n[![pip-tools overview for phase II][pip-tools-overview]][pip-tools-overview]\n\n## Installation\n\nSimilar to `pip`, `pip-tools` must be installed in each of your project's\n[virtual environments](https://packaging.python.org/tutorials/installing-packages/#creating-virtual-environments):\n\n```console\n$ source /path/to/venv/bin/activate\n(venv) $ python -m pip install pip-tools\n```\n\n**Note**: all of the remaining example commands assume you've activated your\nproject's virtual environment.\n\n## Example usage for `pip-compile`\n\nThe `pip-compile` command lets you compile a `requirements.txt` file from\nyour dependencies, specified in either `pyproject.toml`, `setup.cfg`,\n`setup.py`, or `requirements.in`.\n\nRun it with `pip-compile` or `python -m piptools compile` (or\n`pipx run --spec pip-tools pip-compile` if `pipx` was installed with the\nappropriate Python version). If you use multiple Python versions, you can also\nrun `py -X.Y -m piptools compile` on Windows and\n`pythonX.Y -m piptools compile` on other systems.\n\n`pip-compile` should be run from the same virtual environment as your\nproject so conditional dependencies that require a specific Python version,\nor other environment markers, resolve relative to your project's\nenvironment.\n\n**Note**: If `pip-compile` finds an existing `requirements.txt` file that\nfulfils the dependencies then no changes will be made, even if updates are\navailable. To compile from scratch, first delete the existing\n`requirements.txt` file, or see\n[Updating requirements](#updating-requirements)\nfor alternative approaches.\n\n### Requirements from `pyproject.toml`\n\nThe `pyproject.toml` file is the\n[latest standard](https://peps.python.org/pep-0621/) for configuring\npackages and applications, and is recommended for new projects. `pip-compile`\nsupports both installing your `project.dependencies` as well as your\n`project.optional-dependencies`. Thanks to the fact that this is an\nofficial standard, you can use `pip-compile` to pin the dependencies\nin projects that use modern standards-adhering packaging tools like\n[Setuptools](https://setuptools.pypa.io), [Hatch](https://hatch.pypa.io/)\nor [flit](https://flit.pypa.io/).\n\nSuppose you have a 'foobar' Python application that is packaged using\n`Setuptools`, and you want to pin it for production. You can declare the\nproject metadata as:\n\n```toml\n[build-system]\nrequires = [\"setuptools\", \"setuptools-scm\"]\nbuild-backend = \"setuptools.build_meta\"\n\n[project]\nrequires-python = \">=3.9\"\nname = \"foobar\"\ndynamic = [\"dependencies\", \"optional-dependencies\"]\n\n[tool.setuptools.dynamic]\ndependencies = { file = [\"requirements.in\"] }\noptional-dependencies.test = { file = [\"requirements-test.txt\"] }\n\n```\n\nIf you have a Django application that is packaged using `Hatch`, and you\nwant to pin it for production. You also want to pin your development tools\nin a separate pin file. You declare `django` as a dependency and create an\noptional dependency `dev` that includes `pytest`:\n\n```toml\n[build-system]\nrequires = [\"hatchling\"]\nbuild-backend = \"hatchling.build\"\n\n[project]\nname = \"my-cool-django-app\"\nversion = \"42\"\ndependencies = [\"django\"]\n\n[project.optional-dependencies]\ndev = [\"pytest\"]\n```\n\nYou can produce your pin files as easily as:\n\n```console\n$ pip-compile -o requirements.txt pyproject.toml\n#\n# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n# by the following command:\n#\n#    pip-compile --output-file=requirements.txt pyproject.toml\n#\nasgiref==3.6.0\n    # via django\ndjango==4.1.7\n    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\nsqlparse==0.4.3\n    # via django\n\n$ pip-compile --extra dev -o dev-requirements.txt pyproject.toml\n#\n# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n# by the following command:\n#\n#    pip-compile --extra=dev --output-file=dev-requirements.txt pyproject.toml\n#\nasgiref==3.6.0\n    # via django\nattrs==22.2.0\n    # via pytest\ndjango==4.1.7\n    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\nexceptiongroup==1.1.1\n    # via pytest\niniconfig==2.0.0\n    # via pytest\npackaging==23.0\n    # via pytest\npluggy==1.0.0\n    # via pytest\npytest==7.2.2\n    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\nsqlparse==0.4.3\n    # via django\ntomli==2.0.1\n    # via pytest\n```\n\nThis is great for both pinning your applications, but also to keep the CI\nof your open-source Python package stable.\n\n### Requirements from `setup.py` and `setup.cfg`\n\n`pip-compile` has also full support for `setup.py`- and\n`setup.cfg`-based projects that use `setuptools`.\n\nJust define your dependencies and extras as usual and run\n`pip-compile` as above.\n\n### Requirements from `requirements.in`\n\nYou can also use plain text files for your requirements (e.g. if you don't\nwant your application to be a package). To use a `requirements.in` file to\ndeclare the Django dependency:\n\n```text\n# requirements.in\ndjango\n```\n\nNow, run `pip-compile requirements.in`:\n\n```console\n$ pip-compile requirements.in\n#\n# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n# by the following command:\n#\n#    pip-compile requirements.in\n#\nasgiref==3.6.0\n    # via django\ndjango==4.1.7\n    # via -r requirements.in\nsqlparse==0.4.3\n    # via django\n```\n\nAnd it will produce your `requirements.txt`, with all the Django dependencies\n(and all underlying dependencies) pinned.\n\n(updating-requirements)=\n\n### Updating requirements\n\n`pip-compile` generates a `requirements.txt` file using the latest versions\nthat fulfil the dependencies you specify in the supported files.\n\nIf `pip-compile` finds an existing `requirements.txt` file that fulfils the\ndependencies then no changes will be made, even if updates are available.\n\nTo force `pip-compile` to update all packages in an existing\n`requirements.txt`, run `pip-compile --upgrade`.\n\nTo update a specific package to the latest or a specific version use the\n`--upgrade-package` or `-P` flag:\n\n```console\n# only update the django package\n$ pip-compile --upgrade-package django\n\n# update both the django and requests packages\n$ pip-compile --upgrade-package django --upgrade-package requests\n\n# update the django package to the latest, and requests to v2.0.0\n$ pip-compile --upgrade-package django --upgrade-package requests==2.0.0\n```\n\nYou can combine `--upgrade` and `--upgrade-package` in one command, to\nprovide constraints on the allowed upgrades. For example to upgrade all\npackages whilst constraining requests to the latest version less than 3.0:\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n```console\n$ pip-compile --upgrade --upgrade-package 'requests<3.0'\n```\n\n### Understanding output file behavior\n\nWhen you run `pip-compile`, it reads any existing output file (e.g.,\n`requirements.txt`) and uses the versions specified there as constraints.\nThis ensures that the output is stable -- `pip-compile` will prefer to\nuse existing pinned versions.\n\nWhen upgrading packages or adding new packages to the input,\nit is possible for the existing pins to conflict with new packages. In such cases,\n`pip-compile` will update the pins and emit a warning\n(e.g., `Discarding foo=1.2.3 to proceed`).\n\nIn order to resolve dependencies afresh, `pip-compile` provides the following options:\n\n- `--upgrade` / `-U` flag to upgrade all packages\n- `--upgrade-package <package>`/`-P <package>` to upgrade specific packages\n\n### Using hashes\n\nIf you would like to use _Hash-Checking Mode_ available in `pip` since\nversion 8.0, `pip-compile` offers `--generate-hashes` flag:\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 18 line-length -->\n```console\n$ pip-compile --generate-hashes requirements.in\n#\n# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n# by the following command:\n#\n#    pip-compile --generate-hashes requirements.in\n#\nasgiref==3.6.0 \\\n    --hash=sha256:71e68008da809b957b7ee4b43dbccff33d1b23519fb8344e33f049897077afac \\\n    --hash=sha256:9567dfe7bd8d3c8c892227827c41cce860b368104c3431da67a0c5a65a949506\n    # via django\ndjango==4.1.7 \\\n    --hash=sha256:44f714b81c5f190d9d2ddad01a532fe502fa01c4cb8faf1d081f4264ed15dcd8 \\\n    --hash=sha256:f2f431e75adc40039ace496ad3b9f17227022e8b11566f4b363da44c7e44761e\n    # via -r requirements.in\nsqlparse==0.4.3 \\\n    --hash=sha256:0323c0ec29cd52bceabc1b4d9d579e311f3e4961b98d174201d5622a23b85e34 \\\n    --hash=sha256:69ca804846bb114d2ec380e4360a8a340db83f0ccf3afceeb1404df028f57268\n    # via django\n```\n\n### Output File\n\nTo output the pinned requirements in a filename other than\n`requirements.txt`, use `--output-file`. This might be useful for compiling\nmultiple files, for example with different constraints on django to test a\nlibrary with both versions using [tox](https://tox.readthedocs.io/en/latest/):\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n```console\n$ pip-compile --upgrade-package 'django<1.0' --output-file requirements-django0x.txt\n$ pip-compile --upgrade-package 'django<2.0' --output-file requirements-django1x.txt\n```\n\nOr to output to standard output, use `--output-file=-`:\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n```console\n$ pip-compile --output-file=- > requirements.txt\n$ pip-compile - --output-file=- < requirements.in > requirements.txt\n```\n\n### Forwarding options to `pip`\n\nAny valid `pip` flags or arguments may be passed on with `pip-compile`'s\n`--pip-args` option, e.g.\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n```console\n$ pip-compile requirements.in --pip-args \"--retries 10 --timeout 30\"\n```\n\n### Configuration\n\nYou can define project-level defaults for `pip-compile` and `pip-sync` by\nwriting them to a configuration file in the same directory as your requirements\ninput files (or the current working directory if piping input from stdin).\nBy default, both `pip-compile` and `pip-sync` will look first\nfor a `.pip-tools.toml` file and then in your `pyproject.toml`. You can\nalso specify an alternate TOML configuration file with the `--config` option.\n\nIt is possible to specify configuration values both globally and command-\nspecific.\nFor example, to by default generate `pip` hashes in the resulting\nrequirements file output, you can specify in a configuration file:\n\n```toml\n[tool.pip-tools]\ngenerate-hashes = true\n```\n\nOptions to `pip-compile` and `pip-sync` that may be used more than once\nmust be defined as lists in a configuration file, even if they only have one\nvalue.\n\n`pip-tools` supports default values for [all valid command-line\nflags](/cli/index.md) of its subcommands. Configuration keys may contain\nunderscores instead of dashes, so the above could also be specified in this\nformat:\n\n```toml\n[tool.pip-tools]\ngenerate_hashes = true\n```\n\nConfiguration defaults specific to `pip-compile` and `pip-sync` can be put\nbeneath separate sections. For example, to by default perform a dry-run with\n`pip-compile`:\n\n```toml\n[tool.pip-tools.compile] # \"sync\" for pip-sync\ndry-run = true\n```\n\nThis does not affect the `pip-sync` command, which also has a `--dry-run`\noption.\nNote that local settings take preference over the global ones of the same name,\nwhenever both are declared, thus this would also make `pip-compile` generate\nhashes, but discard the global dry-run setting:\n\n```toml\n[tool.pip-tools]\ngenerate-hashes = true\ndry-run = true\n\n[tool.pip-tools.compile]\ndry-run = false\n```\n\nYou might be wrapping the `pip-compile` command in another script. To avoid\nconfusing consumers of your custom script you can override the update command\ngenerated at the top of requirements files by setting the\n`CUSTOM_COMPILE_COMMAND` environment variable.\n\n```console\n$ CUSTOM_COMPILE_COMMAND=\"./pipcompilewrapper\" pip-compile requirements.in\n#\n# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n# by the following command:\n#\n#    ./pipcompilewrapper\n#\nasgiref==3.6.0\n    # via django\ndjango==4.1.7\n    # via -r requirements.in\nsqlparse==0.4.3\n    # via django\n```\n\n### Workflow for layered requirements\n\nIf you have different environments that you need to install different but\ncompatible packages for, then you can create layered requirements files and use\none layer to constrain the other.\n\nFor example, if you have a Django project where you want the newest `2.1`\nrelease in production and when developing you want to use the Django debug\ntoolbar, then you can create two `*.in` files, one for each layer:\n\n```text\n# requirements.in\ndjango<2.2\n```\n\nAt the top of the development requirements `dev-requirements.in` you use `-c\nrequirements.txt` to constrain the dev requirements to packages already\nselected for production in `requirements.txt`.\n\n```text\n# dev-requirements.in\n-c requirements.txt\ndjango-debug-toolbar<2.2\n```\n\nFirst, compile `requirements.txt` as usual:\n\n```text\n$ pip-compile\n#\n# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n# by the following command:\n#\n#    pip-compile\n#\ndjango==2.1.15\n    # via -r requirements.in\npytz==2023.3\n    # via django\n```\n\nNow compile the dev requirements and the `requirements.txt` file is used as\na constraint:\n\n```console\n$ pip-compile dev-requirements.in\n#\n# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.10\n# by the following command:\n#\n#    pip-compile dev-requirements.in\n#\ndjango==2.1.15\n    # via\n    #   -c requirements.txt\n    #   django-debug-toolbar\ndjango-debug-toolbar==2.1\n    # via -r dev-requirements.in\npytz==2023.3\n    # via\n    #   -c requirements.txt\n    #   django\nsqlparse==0.4.3\n    # via django-debug-toolbar\n```\n\nAs you can see above, even though a `2.2` release of Django is available, the\ndev requirements only include a `2.1` version of Django because they were\nconstrained. Now both compiled requirements files can be installed safely in\nthe dev environment.\n\nTo install requirements in production stage use:\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n```console\n$ pip-sync\n```\n\nYou can install requirements in development stage by:\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n```console\n$ pip-sync requirements.txt dev-requirements.txt\n```\n\n### Version control integration\n\nYou might use `pip-compile` as a hook for the\n[pre-commit](https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit).\nSee [pre-commit docs](https://pre-commit.com/) for instructions.\nSample `.pre-commit-config.yaml`:\n\n```yaml\nrepos:\n  - repo: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools\n    rev: 7.4.1\n    hooks:\n      - id: pip-compile\n```\n\nYou might want to customize `pip-compile` args by configuring `args` and/or\n`files`, for example:\n\n```yaml\nrepos:\n  - repo: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools\n    rev: 7.4.1\n    hooks:\n      - id: pip-compile\n        files: ^requirements/production\\.(in|txt)$\n        args: [--index-url=https://example.com, requirements/production.in]\n```\n\nIf you have multiple requirement files make sure you create a hook for each\nfile.\n\n```yaml\nrepos:\n  - repo: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools\n    rev: 7.4.1\n    hooks:\n      - id: pip-compile\n        name: pip-compile setup.py\n        files: ^(setup\\.py|requirements\\.txt)$\n      - id: pip-compile\n        name: pip-compile requirements-dev.in\n        args: [requirements-dev.in]\n        files: ^requirements-dev\\.(in|txt)$\n      - id: pip-compile\n        name: pip-compile requirements-lint.in\n        args: [requirements-lint.in]\n        files: ^requirements-lint\\.(in|txt)$\n      - id: pip-compile\n        name: pip-compile requirements.in\n        args: [requirements.in]\n        files: ^requirements\\.(in|txt)$\n```\n\n### Example usage for `pip-sync`\n\nNow that you have a `requirements.txt`, you can use `pip-sync` to update\nyour virtual environment to reflect exactly what's in there. This will\ninstall/upgrade/uninstall everything necessary to match the\n`requirements.txt` contents.\n\nRun it with `pip-sync` or `python -m piptools sync`. If you use multiple\nPython versions, you can also run `py -X.Y -m piptools sync` on Windows and\n`pythonX.Y -m piptools sync` on other systems.\n\n`pip-sync` must be installed into and run from the same virtual\nenvironment as your project to identify which packages to install\nor upgrade.\n\n**Be careful**: `pip-sync` is meant to be used only with a\n`requirements.txt` generated by `pip-compile`.\n\n```console\n$ pip-sync\nUninstalling flake8-2.4.1:\n    Successfully uninstalled flake8-2.4.1\nCollecting click==4.1\n    Downloading click-4.1-py2.py3-none-any.whl (62kB)\n    100% |................................| 65kB 1.8MB/s\n    Found existing installation: click 4.0\n    Uninstalling click-4.0:\n        Successfully uninstalled click-4.0\nSuccessfully installed click-4.1\n```\n\nTo sync multiple `*.txt` dependency lists, just pass them in via command\nline arguments, e.g.\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n```console\n$ pip-sync dev-requirements.txt requirements.txt\n```\n\nPassing in empty arguments would cause it to default to `requirements.txt`.\n\nAny valid `pip install` flags or arguments may be passed with `pip-sync`'s\n`--pip-args` option, e.g.\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 2 commands-show-output -->\n```console\n$ pip-sync requirements.txt --pip-args \"--no-cache-dir --no-deps\"\n```\n\n**Note**: `pip-sync` will not upgrade or uninstall packaging tools like\n`setuptools`, `pip`, or `pip-tools` itself.\nUse `python -m pip install --upgrade` to upgrade those packages.\n\n### Should I commit `requirements.in` and `requirements.txt` to source control?\n\nGenerally, yes. If you want a reproducible environment installation available\nfrom your source control, then yes, you should commit both `requirements.in`\nand `requirements.txt` to source control.\n\nNote that if you are deploying on multiple Python environments (read the\nsection below), then you must commit a separate output file for each Python\nenvironment.\nWe suggest to use the `{env}-requirements.txt` format\n(ex: `win32-py3.7-requirements.txt`, `macos-py3.10-requirements.txt`,\netc.).\n\n### Cross-environment usage of `requirements.in`/`requirements.txt` and `pip-compile`\n\nThe dependencies of a package can change depending on the Python environment in\nwhich it is installed. Here, we define a Python environment as the combination\nof Operating System, Python version (3.7, 3.8, etc.), and Python implementation\n(CPython, PyPy, etc.). For an exact definition, refer to the possible\ncombinations of [PEP 508 environment markers][environment-markers].\n\nAs the resulting `requirements.txt` can differ for each environment, users must\nexecute `pip-compile` **on each Python environment separately** to generate a\n`requirements.txt` valid for each said environment. The same `requirements.in`\ncan be used as the source file for all environments, using\n[PEP 508 environment markers][environment-markers] as needed, the same way it\nwould be done for regular `pip` cross-environment usage.\n\nIf the generated `requirements.txt` remains exactly the same for all Python\nenvironments, then it can be used across Python environments safely. **But**\nusers should be careful as any package update can introduce\nenvironment-dependent dependencies, making any newly generated\n`requirements.txt` environment-dependent too.\nAs a general rule, it's advised that users should still always execute\n`pip-compile` on each targeted Python environment to avoid issues.\n\n### Maximizing reproducibility\n\n`pip-tools` is a great tool to improve the reproducibility of builds.\nBut there are a few things to keep in mind.\n\n- `pip-compile` will produce different results in different environments as\n  described in the previous section.\n- `pip` must be used with the `PIP_CONSTRAINT` environment variable to lock\n  dependencies in build environments as documented in\n  [#8439](https://github.com/pypa/pip/issues/8439).\n- Dependencies come from many sources.\n\nContinuing the `pyproject.toml` example from earlier, creating a single lock\nfile could be done like:\n\n<!-- pyml disable-num-lines 7 line-length -->\n```console\n$ pip-compile --all-build-deps --all-extras --output-file=constraints.txt --strip-extras pyproject.toml\n#\n# This file is autogenerated by pip-compile with Python 3.9\n# by the following command:\n#\n#    pip-compile --all-build-deps --all-extras --output-file=constraints.txt --strip-extras pyproject.toml\n#\nasgiref==3.5.2\n    # via django\nattrs==22.1.0\n    # via pytest\nbackports-zoneinfo==0.2.1\n    # via django\ndjango==4.1\n    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\neditables==0.3\n    # via hatchling\nhatchling==1.11.1\n    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml::build-system.requires)\niniconfig==1.1.1\n    # via pytest\npackaging==21.3\n    # via\n    #   hatchling\n    #   pytest\npathspec==0.10.2\n    # via hatchling\npluggy==1.0.0\n    # via\n    #   hatchling\n    #   pytest\npy==1.11.0\n    # via pytest\npyparsing==3.0.9\n    # via packaging\npytest==7.1.2\n    # via my-cool-django-app (pyproject.toml)\nsqlparse==0.4.2\n    # via django\ntomli==2.0.1\n    # via\n    #   hatchling\n    #   pytest\n```\n\nSome build backends may also request build dependencies dynamically using the\n`get_requires_for_build_` hooks described in [PEP 517] and [PEP 660].\nThis will be indicated in the output with one of the following suffixes:\n\n- `(pyproject.toml::build-system.backend::editable)`\n- `(pyproject.toml::build-system.backend::sdist)`\n- `(pyproject.toml::build-system.backend::wheel)`\n\n### Other useful tools\n\n- [pip-compile-multi](https://pip-compile-multi.rtfd.io) - pip-compile command\n  wrapper for multiple cross-referencing requirements files.\n- [pipdeptree](https://github.com/tox-dev/pipdeptree) to print the dependency\n  tree of the installed packages.\n- `requirements.in`/`requirements.txt` syntax highlighting:\n  - [requirements.txt.vim](https://github.com/raimon49/requirements.txt.vim)\n    for Vim.\n  - [Python extension for VS Code].\n  - [pip-requirements.el](https://github.com/Wilfred/pip-requirements.el) for\n    Emacs.\n\n[Python extension for VS Code]:\nhttps://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=ms-python.python\n\n### Deprecations\n\nThis section lists `pip-tools` features that are currently deprecated.\n\n- In the next major release, the `--allow-unsafe` behavior will be enabled by\n  default (https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/issues/989).\n  Use `--no-allow-unsafe` to keep the old behavior. It is recommended\n  to pass `--allow-unsafe` now to adapt to the upcoming change.\n- The legacy resolver is deprecated and will be removed in future versions.\n  The new default is `--resolver=backtracking`.\n- In the next major release, the `--strip-extras` behavior will be enabled by\n  default (https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/issues/1613).\n  Use `--no-strip-extras` to keep the old behavior.\n\n### A Note on Resolvers\n\nYou can choose from either default backtracking resolver or the deprecated\nlegacy resolver.\n\nThe legacy resolver will occasionally fail to resolve dependencies. The\nbacktracking resolver is more robust, but can take longer to run in general.\n\nYou can continue using the legacy resolver with `--resolver=legacy` although\nnote that it is deprecated and will be removed in a future release.\n\n[jazzband]: https://jazzband.co/\n[jazzband-image]: https://jazzband.co/static/img/badge.svg\n[pypi]: https://pypi.org/project/pip-tools/\n[pypi-image]: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/pip-tools.svg\n[pyversions]: https://pypi.org/project/pip-tools/\n[pyversions-image]: https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/pip-tools.svg\n[pre-commit]: https://results.pre-commit.ci/latest/github/jazzband/pip-tools/main\n[pre-commit-image]: https://results.pre-commit.ci/badge/github/jazzband/pip-tools/main.svg\n[buildstatus-gha]: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/actions?query=workflow%3ACI\n[buildstatus-gha-image]: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/workflows/CI/badge.svg\n[codecov]: https://codecov.io/gh/jazzband/pip-tools\n[codecov-image]: https://codecov.io/gh/jazzband/pip-tools/branch/main/graph/badge.svg\n[Matrix Room Badge]: https://img.shields.io/matrix/pip-tools:matrix.org?label=Discuss%20on%20Matrix%20at%20%23pip-tools%3Amatrix.org&logo=matrix&server_fqdn=matrix.org&style=flat\n[Matrix Room]: https://matrix.to/#/%23pip-tools:matrix.org\n[Matrix Space Badge]: https://img.shields.io/matrix/jazzband:matrix.org?label=Discuss%20on%20Matrix%20at%20%23jazzband%3Amatrix.org&logo=matrix&server_fqdn=matrix.org&style=flat\n[Matrix Space]: https://matrix.to/#/%23jazzband:matrix.org\n[pip-tools-overview]: https://github.com/jazzband/pip-tools/raw/main/img/pip-tools-overview.svg\n[environment-markers]: https://peps.python.org/pep-0508/#environment-markers\n[PEP 517]: https://peps.python.org/pep-0517/\n[PEP 660]: https://peps.python.org/pep-0660/\n[discord-chat]: https://discord.gg/pypa\n[discord-chat-image]: https://img.shields.io/discord/803025117553754132?label=Discord%20chat%20%23pip-tools&style=flat-square\n","numLines":748,"startLine":1,"totalLines":748}}}
